# Differential intellectual progress

Looking at digital preservation from the viewpoint of [Differential intellectual progress](), it is important to note that since archiving old content does not directly produce technological or intellectual advances there are no direct increases in the relevant risks (e.g. the risk of producing harmful nanotechnology).
However it must be noted that there still indirect risks involved; for instance, preserving content regarding certain technologies or promoting blind technological advancement will increase the visibility of such content, which may in turn increase risks.

